<subSubSection lastPageId="190" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="189" pageNumber="190" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="189" pageNumber="190">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="189" pageNumber="190">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 170" captionStartId="F170" captionText="Figure 170. Distribution of Conostegia incurva." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure170" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96528" pageId="189" pageNumber="190">170</figureCitation>
). Endemic to the Pacific slope of the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tilarán">Tilaran</normalizedToken>
, Central and Talamanca Cordilleras in Costa Rica, 500-1500 in elevation.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973995" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure170" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96528" pageId="189" pageNumber="190" start="Figure 170" startId="F170">
<paragraph pageId="189" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="189" pageNumber="190">Figure 170.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia incurva" order="Myrtales" pageId="189" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incurva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="189" pageNumber="190">Conostegia incurva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="190" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia incurva" order="Myrtales" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incurva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">
<pageBreakToken pageId="190" pageNumber="191" start="start">Conostegia</pageBreakToken>
incurva
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species that can be recognized by the ferrugineous indument that covers the abaxial leaf surface, the strongly plinerved leaves with frequently asymmetrical primary veins, and large flowers with linear and evident calyx teeth. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Kriebel" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia schlimii" order="Myrtales" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schlimii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Conostegia schlimii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter lacks the linear calyx teeth. Interestingly, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia incurva" order="Myrtales" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incurva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Conostegia incurva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a strongly supported species pair with the northern Central American endemic 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Donn. Sm." baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oligocephala" order="Myrtales" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oligocephala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Conostegia oligocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the molecular phylogeny. The latter has much smaller flowers and more whitish indument on the leaves abaxially. The specimen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Herrera 627</emphasis>
(CAS, CR) mentions the style separate from the stamens like most other species in section 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Geniculatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Geniculatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
